text:
I have a few tips that might help (and some other explanations):

* First of all, you should really try harder to keep your energy up. Like with Spore Spawn (that plant thing), you kept going in with such low energy, even though they put an enemy spawner right there, between the save station and the mini-boss, for exactly this purpose. Literally the only reason you should ever skip something like that is if you're speedrunning. You can also use things like that to replenish supplies, especially if there's a door you have to use Missiles or whatever to open: open the door, then farm them back before proceeding.
* Like most games from this era, things generally don't happen off-screen (because there just wasn't enough processing power). You often try to shoot things you can't see, but that does nothing because your shots stop existing once they leave the screen. For instance, when you were trying to kill the mini-Kraid from the other side of the room, that accomplished nothing, apart from wasting resources; so don't do that. Enemies also generally don't move when off-screen, though there are some exceptions.
* The problem you were having doing damage to Kraid has to do with how the Charge Beam works. It's not that the shots weren't connecting, it's that the regular beam doesn't damage him, only charged shots. The Charge Beam requires you to hold the button for a certain amount of time (about 1.5 seconds) before you will get an actual charged shot. You can tell it's charged by seeing Samus flashing, and you can easily tell the difference between the shots themselves. Once you gain experience, you should be able to know the required time without watching Samus, and thus get off a charged shot in minimal time.
* There is a "cancel item" button, which always returns your weapon selection to the beam, so you don't have to cycle through them. It's a much more reliable way; I think you would be a lot less likely to waste Supers if you did that. Since you seem to be using the default configuration, it should be set to Y.
* Speaking of which, you can also customize the button assignments for dash, jump, shoot, cancel item, aim up (diagonal), aim down (diagonal), and select item. The menu for this is available when starting a new game, as well as when you load a save.
* The areas in Norfair that drain your health are not filled with water; water never harms Samus, it just hinders her movement. What is in Norfair is superheated air (you're going deeper into the planet, getting closer to its molten core, so this makes sense). Originally, she can't withstand it for very long, but the Varia Suit protects her against it.
* You don't have to bomb blocks that require a certain weapon before you use that weapon. The change in appearance is only so you know, but if you already know, it's fine to just use whatever it needs.
* For the vast majority of the game, you never need to walljump. Walljump is a special trick whose nearly sole purpose is to allow sequence breaking, which I think is pretty awesome. All the way back in 1994, Nintendo developers not only knew about sequence breaking, but actually deliberately provided a tool to facilitate it, in order to increase replayability. And it shows: Super Metroid is one of the most popular games ever for speedrunners, as they continue to find new tricks to shorten the time of a playthrough (while also increasing the time they actually spend playing it overall, and replaying it countless times). Of course, the devs also clearly tried to prevent sequence breaking in some places. But in any case, there is one area that, if you fall into it, you're forced to do just one walljump in order to escape. You have to do more to fully explore the area, but that's optional. So, I don't recommend even thinking about it on a first playthrough. Well, unless you end up in said area. Same goes for Infinite Bomb Jump, without the qualifier (also, IBJ is probably not an intended mechanic, yet it seems they still accounted for it).

text: Having grown up during the nes and snes era, watching the super shork struggle with platforming is painful. It also hurts that game devs just... dropped the whole teaching players by giving them an item and then a puzzle so they learn how to use it... you don't see that anymore. Its all "Here are bombs, make sure you are in morph ball mode in order to use them, they can blow up certain walls and floors, and can help you reach new areas you wouldn't normally be able to reach!"
